Eight characters, a number, and a happy ending

by K.G. Orphanides

Eight characters, a number, and a happy ending is a text adventure set aboard a spacecraft heading into a distant solar system.

The fundamental way of interacting with it is to enter simple commands such as east (e), west (w), north (n) and south (s) to move around its world.

You can also use simple word combinations to interact with the objects you find there.
For example you might want to unlock door, get laser rifle, write book or sit on couch.

This game has an expanded set of less tangible commands that allow you interact with the world and your own mind in specific ways and situations. Finding out what these are and how to best use them is a fundamental part of exploring the game and the questions it presents. While some, relating to the functioning of your spacecraft and its systems, will be explained in manuals that you'll find aboard your ship, others may require a greater leap of intuition.

Infinite thanks to my beta testers: D. Ellis, C. Slee, B. Wilson, R. Alexander, D. Lodge, A. Webb.

You may die. This is not necessarily a problem.

"The supreme art of war is to subdue the enemy without fighting."
-- Sun Tzu, The Art of War

You are in the Control Room.

The monotony of featureless grey and white walls is alleviated only by the occasional appearance of the Earth Alliance insignia. It's not much of an improvement. Years ago, control would have been the bustling heart of any ship. In the latest single-crew, single-AI vessels, it's an empty room that contains only an acceleration couch, a small info screen, and a documentation tablet, tethered to the couch so it doesn't get lost amid all the clutter.

You can see a screen, an acceleration couch and a document file.
You can go east, north, west or south.
> east

> east

You are in the Medbay.

Storage lockers line the walls, but there's little sign that they are used regularly. An examination table lies at the cente of the room, with a screen and a range of medical apparatus attached to it.

You can see an examination table and a screen.
You can go west or north.
> lie on examination table

> lie on examination table
As you settle down on the examination table, the instruments surronding it whirr into life. The screen swivels to display a message:

THANK YOU FOR YOUR COOPERATION, CAPTAIN.
PLEASE RELAX WHILE THE SYSTEM CARRIES OUT BASIC INTEGRATION TESTS.

The process is familiar. You lie back and close your eyes while the machines make themselves busy about your person, prodding and measuring you. After some time, the whirring ceases, the machines retract, and you are presented with a new message on the screen:

PHYSICAL HEALTH: OPTIMAL
MENTAL HEALTH: OPTIMAL
INTEGRATION: MULTIPLE ERRORS

The system has failed to correctly integrate your memories with your body upon revival from stasis.
You are in otherwise excellent health and we hope that your memories may return in time.
In the interim, please refer to documentation in the crew quarters and ship's archive for backgound information on your mission. The ship's computer is at your disposal should you have any further questions.

ARCHIVE: UNLOCKED
COMMS: UNLOCKED
CREW QUARTERS: UNLOCKED

