> examine game board

> examine game board
The game board is in fact a medium-sized table, larger than the main comms console itself. A concave metal surface conceals an array of holographic projectors. It is currently switched off.
> press play

> press play
You stare at the flickering holographic images that cover the game board.

Your ranked and fortified Earth Alliance marines seem to stretch for kilometres across the shimmering holographic plain. You set up your victory by the book, following the original battle plans recorded by Alliance historians as an eternal tribute to the military action that wiped out the empire of the first xeno race the EA ever came up against. Unfortunately, your opponent has clearly not been playing by the same book.

Suddenly, as if from nowhere, the red-carapaced insectoid shock troops burst from the dusty earth and dry blue grass. Your marines had already stripped out all the trees and levelled all the hills for as far as the eye can see, but somehow, the bugs were still able to get a rush on you.

Beneath your forces' feet, the soil gives way, and your entire army plunges into a deep, suffocating sinkhole, many kilometres in diameter. It doesn't take your opponent's ground forces long to mop up the few surviving remnants of your once-great legions.

The comms system announces that you have a new message waiting.
> read message 4

> read message 4
Subject: FINAL MESSAGE
From: Aleph

"If you know the enemy and know yourself, you need not fear the result of a hundred battles. If you know yourself but not the enemy, for every victory gained you will also suffer a defeat. If you know neither the enemy nor yourself, you will succumb in every battle. " - Sun Tzu

If you do not know yourself, how can you ever know who your enemy really is?

By the time you receive this message, you should have come out of stasis for the final approach to the Iastrai system, and  I will, I hope, no longer be alive.

Know yourself.
Know your enemy.
REMEMBER.
> computer who am i?

