> remember

> remember
You try to think back, to recall any detail of your life, your training, the time before the wall. Waves of sense-memory wash over you, but the details slip away as you try to grasp them. You grope for anything you've seen or done that could trigger your ability to recall...

Your service pistol feels heavy at your belt. You recall the sensation of a cold muzzle pressed against your temple, your hand on the trigger.

They took you at a march against the war on the Iastrai. The Earth Aliance called it a war. They meant that they wanted the Iastrai's worlds and orbitals. So like us in so many ways, they built, discovered, and terraformed habitats idea for human habitation millenia before we so much as set foot outside our own solar system. The old, now excised, contact reports from those first meetings with them said that they had no military infrastucture, no history of civil or extraterritorial war. If a planet was occupied, they left it. If it was home to non-sentient life, the adapted their colonists, rather than the world. They signed a peace treaty with our ancestors and went on their merry way, turning barren rocks into thriving garden worlds in their wake.

You clung to Aleph when when you realised the EA peacekeepers were loading the protesters from the kettle into recruitment trucks. They shot the SmartDogs in front of you, jammed the mindlink channel you shared. As they pulled you apart, you swore that you would never forget that day. That date.

It was never entirely clear why they allowed you to remain in touch with Aleph after recruitment. After the first round of memory enhancement and training, they promised that you'd be able to exchange letters as a reward and they were as good as their word. Then again, training was nothing like you expected it to be. You thought they'd wipe your memories of the past. Instead, you were just given a different perspective. As you both progressed through the ranks, your radical past became a shared joke between you as you poured your loyalty and faith into the service. Right now, it's hard to remember what was so funny about it.

You've not been yourself for a very long time. You aren't really yourself now nor will you ever be again. The person you once were most likely ceased to exist on the day of the protests on Luna, when you lost Aleph, the SmartDogs and the right to control the way you felt about your own memories, all in a single day.

You are no longer the bastion of Earth Alliance values that trained for this mission. The values you operate under and the choices you make are your own again. It's amazing how little comfort that provides.

When you read your own journal, it was like looking through the life of another person. For all that you're having trouble remembering them, you have the same life experiences as both that loyal soldier of the Alliance and the dissident who was dragged away during the Luna protests. But you're not either of these people. Any decisions you make will be your own. If you can learn enough to make them in time.
